India's New Hope
Cambridge, US—India's latest election may be the most significant positive economic event of 2014.
India's voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which had nearly always ruled India since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be happy with this decision.
The President of the Congress Party and former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's widow Sonia Gandhi has been de facto ruling the country since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh is nothing but a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfers and leading to India's economic growth rate plummeting to below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP is still hovering around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi has committed to bringing rapid job and income growth to all of India, just as he did in Gujarat as Chief Minister.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with economic activity expanding and attracting business investment from both within and outside India.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the National Assembly, an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will assist Modi on economic planning.
The newly appointed Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has rich political experience, having held a ministerial position in the previous BJP government.
Jaitley is also known for his strategic thinking as a champion of business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India. Rajan, an outstanding economist, has shown a desire to reduce India's high double-digit inflation rate while in office, and has attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and produce results.
But to find out whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should look for progress in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India boasts excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of people can avail themselves of the opportunities offered by these institutions due to the backwardness of primary and secondary education in India.
Only about 60% of Indian adults have the literacy skills of a primary school level.
Teachers themselves have a mediocre educational background, lack work motivation, and many teachers rarely even show up at the schools they are supposed to teach at.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport goods across the country and around the world.
Recent expansion of private air routes and airports indicates that private enterprise can also make a difference in this field.
Financial integration.
Large budget deficits are absorbing household savings, which could otherwise be used to boost business investment. The budget deficits are leading to an increase in national debt that will have to be financed by future tax revenues.
Privatization.
India's government-run manufacturing and other industries operate at low efficiency, often leading to the absorption of household savings.
Selling off these enterprises would directly help accelerate economic growth.
Phasing out subsidies.
Energy and power subsidies have led to wasteful overconsumption and an increase in budget deficits.
Although it is difficult to cancel these subsidies politically, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, with the introduction of the notable fingerprint-based cash transfer system, India's cash transfer payment efficiency is high.
Agricultural reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is a large accumulation of goods in warehouses, while production incentives have been misdirected.
Privatization of the agricultural market.
Privatization and regional decentralization.
Only those who have visited Mumbai or other major Indian cities will see that regional decentralization has restricted the efficient use of urban land, constraining its development.
Lack of clear property rights, particularly those related to agricultural land, has hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Relaxation of foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign companies cannot be the majority shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions can bolster the financial sector and play a crucial role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex system of central and state sales taxes has distorted domestic trade.
The debate on replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a dual-tax system has been ongoing for a long time, and it is now time to move to implementation.
Corruption.
High-profile corruption cases have undermined economic confidence, and also hindered official decision-making.
India is also plagued by petty corruption, with bribery becoming a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should strictly punish high-level corruption, and curb petty corruption through a new system of cash transfer payments.
Driven by strong growth and increasing profit expectations, the Indian stock market has risen by 20% so far this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP must demonstrate to the world that they can deliver on their campaign promises.
